      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Commercial CFD solver with documented V&V history; version-controlled simulation scripts; audit trail for all simulation inputs and outputs.",
      "rationale": "ANSYS Fluent 2022 R2 was used under a validated installation qualification protocol. All simulation scripts are stored in a version-controlled repository (Git SHA documented). Input deck review and independent re-run checks were completed by a second analyst. SQA level 2 requirements are satisfied."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Solver passes published benchmark test cases relevant to rotating-frame turbulent flow; documented convergence of manufactured-solution tests.",
      "rationale": "ANSYS Fluent passes the FDA benchmark hemolysis test case (Hariharan et al.) and the rotating-frame Taylor-Couette verification suite. Manufactured-solution convergence rates are second-order in space, consistent with the solver's documented discretization scheme. Code verification requirements at level 2 are met."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Grid convergence index (GCI) < 5% for NIH QoI on the finest two mesh levels; mesh independence demonstrated across three refinement levels.",
      "rationale": "Three structured hexahedral meshes (2.1 M, 6.4 M, 18.7 M cells) were generated for the nominal CPB geometry. Richardson extrapolation yields GCI_fine = 3.1% for NIH at the worst-case operating point (4.5 L/min, 2800 RPM). Discretization error is within the level 2 acceptance threshold."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental test conditions used in validation activities are documented with sufficient detail to enable replication; boundary conditions in CFD match test conditions within stated tolerances.",
      "rationale": "The Graefe et al. (2022) dataset reports fluid temperature (37 ± 0.5 °C), hematocrit (30 ± 1%), blood analogue composition, and inlet/outlet pressure boundary conditions. CFD boundary conditions were set to match reported test values. Note: the Graefe dataset was acquired at 3500 RPM and 5 L/min for a VAD application; the CPB COU operates at 2000–3000 RPM and 2.5–5.0 L/min. The assessment team considers the overlap in flow rate sufficient for validation purposes; the rotational speed difference is noted but not evaluated for its effect on shear-stress scaling and hemolysis index."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric (RH) computed and reported for all validation operating points; comparison includes uncertainty quantification for both simulation and experimental outputs.",
      "rationale": "RH values were computed for all five CPB operating points relative to the Graefe dataset. RH ranged from 0.71 to 0.94 across the five points. Experimental measurement uncertainty (±8% NIH at 95% CI) and CFD numerical uncertainty (GCI-based, ±3.1%) were propagated into the RH calculation. All RH values remain below 1.0 even at the upper uncertainty bound, satisfying the acceptance criterion."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs used in validation (NIH, RH) are directly linked to the clinical decision question (worst-case hemolysis identification); QoI definitions are consistent between simulation and experiment.",
      "rationale": "NIH is the standard hemolysis metric for rotary blood pumps per ASTM F1841 and ISO 10993-4. The relative hemolysis index RH directly addresses the COU question of whether the CPB device produces hemolysis exceeding the predicate. QoI definitions are consistent between the CFD power-law hemolysis model and the Graefe experimental protocol."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activities address the same device class, fluid regime, and operating domain as the COU; any differences between validation scenario and COU are documented and their impact on credibility is evaluated.",
      "rationale": "The validation activity uses a centrifugal blood pump geometry comparable to the FDA generic pump and employs blood-analogue fluid at physiological hematocrit, consistent with the CPB COU. The Graefe dataset is described as highly relevant by the assessment team on account of geometric similarity and matching flow rate. The assessment team notes that the Graefe experiments were performed under VAD operating conditions (higher rotational speed and pressure head than CPB) but concludes that the geometric and fluid-property similarity is the dominant factor governing hemolysis prediction credibility. The impact of the rotational-speed difference on the shear-stress distribution and its effect on the power-law hemolysis model exponent is not quantitatively evaluated."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Not required at MRL 2 for this factor.",
      "rationale": "Per ASME V&V 40 Table 3, numerical solver error is not required to be independently assessed at MRL 2 when code verification has been completed at level 2 or above. This factor is scoped out of the MRL 2 assessment."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Not required at MRL 2.",
      "rationale": "Use error assessment is not required at MRL 2. Simulation execution was performed by an experienced analyst with documented training records; informal controls are considered adequate at this risk level."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Not required at MRL 2.",
      "rationale": "Formal model-form uncertainty quantification is not required at MRL 2. The power-law hemolysis model (Giersiepen-Wurzinger) is the accepted standard for CFD hemolysis prediction in regulatory submissions; its limitations are acknowledged in the literature but not formally quantified here."
    },
